Commit Message: DATA: Added lite pattern data file with git lfs
Update Django middleware to be compatible with Django 1.10
Update TRIE.txt
Updated TRIE.txt
BUG: Cache performance impacted if NDEBUG is not defined.

BUG: distribute package is depricated and has been replaced by setuptools.
Although distribute is a wrapper for setuptools, installation of distribute causes installation to fail on newer versions of pip/setuptools.
FEAT: Mozilla Public License Version 2.0 displayed in GitHub markdown.

BUG: User-Agent cache in the shared memory zone lock was not released in the rare case when an identical match had been inserted in the time between getting a match and adding it to the cache.
If a node is not inserted, then the mutex unlock call is now reached.
closes #17

FEAT: 51D_match methods can now be called from http and server blocks.
Any match headers which are set in HTTP or server blocks are applied in
the locations within their hierarchy.

closes #11

BUG: Nginx now frees a previously allocated dataset if the config is reloaded.
Previously, a new shared memory zone was created. However, now the same
shared memory zone is created, so if there is already a dataset in there
is freed before initialising a new one.

closes #18
DOC: Added section on version support policy.

DOC: Instructions to build module for PHP 7 are now clearer.
This was instigated by a support request asking whether we support PHP 7 or not.

BUILD: Added a check for node version when installing.
Versions 7 and above are not supported, so a message is displayed.
DATA: Updated Lite data files for September 2017.

FEAT: Implemented new Hash Trie V34 algorithm. This replaces the old Trie algorithm with the same public interface and gives much improved speed and memory overhead.
A full rundown of how the new algorithm performs in comparison to the old one can be found at https://51degrees.com/blog/51degrees-more-than-three-times-faster-1.
To aid easy updating, and keep the repository clean, Hash Trie data files are hosted on distributor.51Degrees.com, and a free licence key can be obtained at https://51degrees.com/products/store/on-premise-device-detection.

Commit Message: FEAT: Added Java Hash Trie implementation.
DOC: Updated patent statements.
BUG: Addressed build errors in Nginx and freed the shared memory in the correct place.
TEST/OPTIM: All tests now check for the data file before running, and the tollerance example only print the matched User-Agents in debug.
BUILD: Updated version numbers.

BUILD: Updated Nginx pre-compiled modules.

Also addressed build issue with pattern.

OPTIM: Added LibLoader class to Java to aid loading the DLL/SO library.
This can just be called to load the native library from the JAR making loading it simpler.

BUG: Nginx shared memory locks were not being properly handled.

The cache is now locked until the result of the cache fetch is finished
with. The dataset cleanup now ensures that only one process attempts to
free the dataset, and that it is the last process to exit which does so.

Pre-compiled modules have also been rebuilt with this fix, and the makefile optimised to build the modules without the need to build the entire Nginx binary.

OPTIM: Improved performance when used in a multi-threaded environment.
Interlocks are now used to track in use sets of devices (offsets). These avoid the need to lock the provider when starting a match or finishing one whilst retaining the ability to reload the data set used with the provider.
The threading code has been updated to provide wrappers for interlocked increment and decrement which operate in MSVC, GCC and Clang.

OPTIM: Improved performance when used with SWIG and C++.
New methods have been added to provide the option to return Boolean, Integer and Double data types rather than strings that are then converted in the target language to these types. These methods are faster and more useful.
A getMatchForByteArray method has also been added for Java which avoids string allocation and copying steps while interfacing between Java and C. This can be called from Java using the string.getBytes() method.
Values can now be fetched using the property index. This bypasses the step which searches for the index using the property name, speeding up getting values for scenarios where many values are fetched.
All getValue methods have been consolidated so that the target language string type is always used.
BUILD: Updated version numbers.
OPTIM: Newer Hash Trie files are written with the length of the string including the null terminator. This means that this does not need to added when allocating memory for a string in indirect mode.
FEAT: Added features and tests to Nginx, also fixed some bugs.
DATA: Updated the Lite Binary file for November 2017.
FEAT: Added Lua module. This is currently in beta, and supports the core functionality. Examples are included as with other modules. See readme for details.

FEAT: 51Degrees PHP common API.

The new 51Degrees PHP common API aims to make switch from Cloud based Device-Detection to the On-Premise version much easier for developers. It allows developers to switch without the need to refactor code by providing a common API between the two solutions connected by an interface which communicates with the core software.
CLEANUP: Cast header to char* in Varnish module to remove compiler warning.
BUILD/OPTIM: Lua build script generates required folders if the do not exist.
DOC: Clarified dependency information.
OPTIM: PHP common API auto update, can now update HashTrie files.
CLEANUP: Remove old project files, update UAs in unit tests.
BUILD: Updated pre-built SWIG generated wrappers.
BUILD: Updated version numbers.
DATA: Updated the Lite data file for February 2018.
DOC: Added guidance on having '--with-compat' available under nginx's configure arguments.
EXAMPLE: Added Hash Trie benchmarks to the Perl, Python, PHP and Node.js wrappers.
FEAT: Go API released.
DOC: Nginx and Varnish no longer in beta.
FEAT: Go API improvements.
DATA: Updated Lite Binary file for April 2018
DOC: Updated README.md with Go information.

BUG: When parameter matches were used alongside caching, proxied requests would contain null headers.

Only the HTTP header matches were cached, so if there were only matches
on a parameter, there was nothing to cache. However, the node was cached
anyway. This meant that when the node was retrieved from the cache in a
subsequent request, there was a problem when proxying the request to
another server due to a null header being added.

Caching is now keyed on both the HTTP headers, and any parameters that
are to be matched. Adding a node to the cache now occurs after all
matching has been carried out. This ensures all matches are treated in
the same way and dealt with by the cache.
DOC: Added GDPR disclaimer for consumer reference.
DATA: Updated the Lite files for May data.
Changes made as part of node.js release

RELEASE: Multiple varnish version support & minor PHP bug fix

- FEAT: Included copying source files into the build process.
- BUILD/BUG: Amended build process to take into consideration the multiple versions of Varnish that were not supported and as a result throwing a segfault when starting the module . Also added additional error logging for when the module fails to start.
- FEAT: Added functionality to switch the module build based on the Varnish version.
- BUILD/DOC: Changed data file check to use a warning message as opposed to error. Update README with additional Hash and build instructions.
- FEAT/DOC/OPTIM: Added Varnish Hash API, added documentation and improved memory allocation
- BUILD: Included SWIG PHP changes in SWIG generated C files.
- BUILD: Improved support for newer Visual Studio versions.

RELEASE: Improved version support and features for NodeJS API

- Reinstated the hash (aka trie) build configuration for Node / NPM.
- Added support for Node 6.5 to 8.
- Set new versions for all NPM packages.
- Modified tests and examples to use the hash (aka trie) data file package.
- Modified contact details to ensure requests are received by 51Degrees support group and not one individual.
- Modified the readme to highlight the full command line.
- Updated SWIG wrapper for node using latest development build of SWIG v4.
- Use "latest" dependency as opposed to version numbers to more elegantly support v3 NPM.
BUG: NPM requires explicit version number within package.json for publishing and testing process.

Merged PR 1697: BUILD/BUG: Update Nginx Makefile to use an up to date stable release, and fixed bug in PHP common API.

- BUILD: Updated Nginx Makefile to use an up to date stable release.
- BUG: When using an on-premise provider through the PHP common API, a memory leak could occur depending on the PHP setup.
Using the on-premise provider directly gets the existing provider, but the common API created a new provider each time. This adds an extra overhead to the request and could result in a memory leak depending on the PHP setup.
This has now been changed to access the existing provider in the same was as directly using the on-premise provider.

BUG: Fixed memory leak when reloading the provider with a GNU compiled library.

The `FIFTYONEDEGREES_INTERLOCK_INC` and `FIFTYONE_DEGREES_INTERLOCK_DEC`
macros were not consistent across MSVC and GNU comilers. The
`_InterlockedDecrement` method returns the value after decrementing
(similarly for the increment method). However, the
`__sync_fetch_and_add` method returns the value before decrementing (or
incrementing). This meant that the `inUse` counter may not be evaluated
as 0, and therefore not allow the provider to be freed.
The GNU implementation now uses `__sync_add_and_fetch` instead of
`__sync_fetch_and_fetch` so that the logic of the macros agrees with the
usage.
